V{{Infobox scientist\u000a| name = Yuri Matiyasevich\u000a| image =Yuri Matiyasevich. Portrait 1969.jpg\u000a| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1947|3|2|mf=y}}\u000a| birth_place = [[Leningrad]], [[Soviet Union]]\u000a|residence = Soviet Union<br> Russia\u000a|nationality = Soviet<br>Russian \u000a| field = [[Mathematics]] and [[Theoretical computer science]]\u000a| known_for  = his contribution to [[computability theory (computer science)|computability theory]], especially\u000a solving [[Hilbert's tenth problem]]\u000a| work_institution = [[LOMI|Petersburg Department]] of [[Steklov Institute of Mathematics]]\u000a| alma_mater = [[Saint Petersburg State University|Leningrad State University]]\u000a|prizes = [[Petersburg Mathematical Society]] Prize (1970),<br>Markov Prize (1980),<br>\u000a[[The Humboldt Prize|Humboldt Award]] (1998)\u000a}}\u000a'''Yuri Vladimirovich Matiyasevich''', ({{lang-ru|\u042e\u0301\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u044f\u0441\u0435\u0301\u0432\u0438\u0447}}; born March 2, 1947, in [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]]) is a [[Russia]]n [[mathematician]] and [[List of computer scientists|computer scientist]]. He is best known for his negative solution of [[Hilbert's tenth problem]] ([[Matiyasevich's theorem]]), presented in his [[doctoral thesis]], at [[LOMI]] (the Leningrad Department of the [[Steklov Institute of Mathematics]]).\u000a\u000a== Biography ==\u000a\u000a* In 1962\u20131963, Matiyasevich studied at [[Saint Petersburg Lyceum 239]];  	\u000a* In 1963\u20131964, he studied at [http://www.pms.ru/glavnaya/1.html Kolmogorov School];\u000a* In 1964\u20131969, Matiyasevich studied at [http://www.math.spbu.ru/en/ Mathematics & Mechanics Faculty] of [[Saint Petersburg State University|Leningrad State University]]. As a winner of [[International Mathematical Olympiad|IMO]] Yuri Matiyasevich was accepted without exams to [[Saint Petersburg State University|LSU]], skipping the last year of high school studies.\u000a* In 1966, he presented a talk at [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] held in [[Moscow]]. He was a second-year undergraduate student at that time.\u000a* In 1969\u20131970, he pursued Ph.D. studies at [[LOMI|Leningrad Department]] of [[Steklov Institute of Mathematics]] under supervision of [http://www.mathsoc.spb.ru/pers/maslov/ Sergey Maslov]. \u000a* In 1970, he received his Ph.D. degree at [[LOMI]].\u000a* In 1970\u20131974, he was a researcher at [[LOMI]]. \u000a* In 1972, he obtained a second doctoral degree (called "doktor nauk" in [[Soviet Union]]).\u000a* In 1974\u20131980, he was a senior researcher at [[LOMI]]. \u000a* Since 1980, Yuri Matiyasevich has been the head of [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru Laboratory of mathematical logic] at [[LOMI]].\u000a* Since 1995, he has been a professor of [[Saint Petersburg State University|Saint-Petersburg State University]], initially at the chair of software engineering, later at the chair of algebra and number theory. \u000a* In 1997, he was elected as a corresponding member of [[Russian Academy of Sciences]].\u000a* Since 1998, Yuri Matiyasevich has been a vice-president of [[St. Petersburg Mathematical Society]].\u000a* Since 2002, he has been a head of [http://www.pdmi.ras.ru/~olymp/ St.Petersburg City Mathematical Olympiad].\u000a* Since 2003, Matiyasevich has been a co-director of annual German\u2013Russian student school [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/jass07/ JASS].\u000a* In 2008, he was elected as a full member of [[Russian Academy of Sciences]].\u000a\u000a== Awards and honors ==\u000a\u000a* 1964: gold medal at the [[International Mathematical Olympiad]] held in [[Moscow]].\u000a* 1970:  "Young mathematician prize" of the [[St. Petersburg Mathematical Society|Leningrad Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.mathsoc.spb.ru/prizes.html]</ref>\u000a* 1980: Markov Prize of [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Academy of Sciences of the USSR]].\u000a* 1996: Honorary Degree, Université d'Auvergne.\u000a* 1998: he received [[The Humboldt Prize|Humboldt Research Award to Outstanding Scholars]].\u000a* 2003: Honorary Degree, [[Université Pierre et Marie Curie]] (UPMC).\u000a* 2007: Member of the [[Bavaria|Bayern]] Academy of Sciences.\u000a\u000a== Notable facts ==\u000a\u000a* A polynomial related to colorings of triangulation of sphere was named after Matiyasevich; see [http://www.pdmi.ras.ru/~duzhin/papers/mati-pol.ps.gz The Matiyasevich polynomial, four colour theorem and weight systems].\u000a* He was a member of the [[American Mathematical Society]] and the [[Association for Symbolic Logic]]; and also of the editorial boards for the journals [https://web.archive.org/web/20070405101041/http://www.vsppub.com/journals/jn-DisMatApp.html Discrete Mathematics and Applications] and [http://www.ipo.spb.ru/journal/ Computer Instruments in Education].\u000a* Notable students include: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070112070241/http://www.eldar.com/eldar/eldar.htm Eldar Musayev], [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~vsemir/ Maxim Vsemirnov], [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~pastor/ Alexei Pastor], [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~dvk/ Dmitri Karpov].\u000a\u000a== Selected works ==\u000a\u000a=== Book ===\u000a*Yuri Matiyasevich [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~yumat/H10Pbook/index.html  ''Hilbert's 10th Problem''], Foreword by [[Martin Davis]] and [[Hilary Putnam]], The MIT Press, 1993. ISBN 0-262-13295-8.\u000a\u000a=== Papers ===\u000a* {{cite journal |author=Yuri Matiyasevich |title=Real-time recognition of the inclusion relation |url=http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~yumat/Journal/inclusion/inclusion.pdf |journal=Journal of Sovjet Mathematics |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=64&ndash;70 |year=1973 |issn=0090-4104 |doi=10.1007/bf01117471}}\u000a* {{cite journal |author=Yuri Matiyasevich, [[Julia Robinson]] |title=Reduction of an arbitrary Diophantine equation to one in 13 unknowns |url=http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~yumat/Journal/reduction/reduction.html |journal=[[Acta Arithmetica]] |volume=XXVII |year=1975 |pages=521\u2013549}}\u000a* {{cite journal |author=Yuri Matiyasevich, [[Géraud Sénizergues]] |title=Decision Problems for Semi-Thue Systems with a Few Rules |url=http://dept-info.labri.u-bordeaux.fr/~ges/termination.ps |journal=LICS |year=1996}}\u000a* Yuri Matiyasevich, [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~yumat/Journal/corte.ps.gz ''Proof Procedures as Bases for Metamathematical Proofs in Discrete Mathematics''], Personal Journal of Yury Matiyasevich. \u000a* Yuri Matiyasevich, [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/Hilbert10/journal/preprints/yumat97a.ps ''Elimination of bounded universal quantifiers standing in front of a quantifier-free arithmetical formula''], Personal Journal of Yuri Matiyasevich.\u000a* Yuri Matiyasevich, [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~yumat/Journal/Triangular/triang.htm ''A Polynomial related to Colourings of Triangulation of Sphere''], Personal Journal of Yuri Matiyasevich.\u000a* {{cite journal |author=Yuri Matiyasevich |url=http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~yumat/Journal/prob4cc/prob4cc.ps.gz |title=Some Probabilistic Restatements of the Four Color Conjecture |journal=Journal of Graph Theory |year=2004 |volume=46 |issue=3 |pages=167\u2013179 |doi=10.1002/jgt.10178}}\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a* [[Matiyasevich's theorem]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a{{commons category|Yuri Matiyasevich (mathematician)}}\u000a* [http://logic.pdmi.ras.ru/~yumat/ Yuri Matiyasevich's home page].\u000a* [http://www.informatik.uni-trier.de/~ley/db/indices/a-tree/m/Matiyasevich:Yuri.html Yuri Matiyasevich at DBLP].\u000a* [http://www.goldenmuseum.com/1612Hilbert_engl.html Hilbert's Tenth Problem: a History of Mathematical Discovery].\u000a* {{IMO results|id=9909}}\u000a* [http://www.scholarpedia.org/article/Matiyasevich_theorem Matiyasevich theorem] on Scholarpedia.\u000a* [http://www.liafa.jussieu.fr/~ig/vita_fr.html Vita and collaboration with France] {{fr icon}}.\u000a* {{MacTutor Biography|id=Matiyasevic